# Riddler: Null Set



The rain hammered against the gargoyle I was perched on. Three live bombs. Three locations. Riddler's sick game was spread across my city like a cancer. Robin was trying to find a pattern in the chaos, but he was looking at the victims, at the fear. He was looking at the endgame. That's how you lose.

You don't solve a puzzle this vile. You shatter it.

Riddler thinks his traps are unique works of art. One is a pressure plate wired to a children's hospital. Another is a poison gas dispenser in the subway. The last is an electrocution grid in the financial district. He sees poetry; I see three strands of the same rotten rope.

He's arrogant, and he's lazy. He reused code. His encryption is a set of recycled keys, a pathetic attempt to save time. Forget the grand design. Find the single, grimy line of code shared between the hospital bomb and the subway trap. Isolate it. Then, find the different sequence that links the hospital bomb to the financial district grid.
